Built-in actions in JIRA have a nice 'roles-required' attribute in actions.xml, which ensures that the request is coming in as a secure request.  This feature currently doesn't work for plugins, so plugin authors could be creating insecure administrative actions without knowing it.

The problem is in how the roles-required attribute is read.  Only the Atlassian Seraph filter (specifically WebworkService) reads this attribute and only by manually parsing the 'actions.xml' file.  Obviously plugins' webwork configuration won't be there, so the attribute is never read.  Ideally, this WebworkService would use loaded action configuration data from Configuration, which would include the plugin actions.  Unfortunately, the 'roles-required' attribute isn't stored in the Webwork configuration, so this isn't currently possible, and Webwork 1 has no way to read in additional action configuration automatically (WebWork 2 has a <param> element for actions where static values can be injected into the action class or read by an interested interceptor).

The workaround I've found involves overriding the execute() method for the Action class, as this method is called whether a command (someaction!somecommand) has been specified or not.  Borrowing code from Seraph, it looks like this:

{code}
public String execute() throws Exception
{
    if (hasRole(request.getUserPrincipal(), request, "admin"))
        return super.execute();
    else
    {
        HttpServletResponse response = ServletActionContext.getResponse();
        response.sendRedirect(RedirectUtils.getLoginUrl(request));
        return null;
    }
}

protected boolean hasRole(Principal user, HttpServletRequest request, String role)
{
    final int permissionType = Permissions.getType(role);
    if (permissionType == -1)
    {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Unknown role '" + role + "'");
    }
    return ManagerFactory.getPermissionManager().hasPermission(permissionType, (User) user);
}
{code}

Notice I'm using the literal "admin", since there is no current way to access the value specified in 'roles-required'.  The RedirectUtils class is actually a Seraph class, and handles the proper creation of the login url, including the destination value.

