 In a JIRA plugin, we might have a module defined with:

{code:xml}
<webwork1 key="HelloWorld" name="Hello World Action Example" i18n-name-key="action.hello.world.name">
  <description key="action.hello.world.desc">Webwork plugin example that prints hello world.</description>
  <resource type="i18n" name="i18n" location="com.atlassian.jira.web.action.HelloWorldAction" />
....
{code}

Normally in plugin internationalization, if a key isn't found in the resource, JIRA falls back to the inline text. For example, if our 'i18n-name-key' property ("action.hello.world.name") wasn't found in HelloWorldAction.properties, the action name would become "Hello World Action Example".

This isn't the case for the description attribute. Here, if key "action.hello.world.desc" isn't found, JIRA uses "action.hello.world.desc". It should fall back to "Webwork plugin example that prints hello world.".

The problem also affects web-item labels. The lack of fallback here means (at least) web-item plugins cannot be internationalized without breaking in untranslated environments.

